input: {
    "response": "The LLM-as-a-judge approach uses a large language model (LLM) to evaluate AI agent outputs as a scalable alternative to human judgment. Instead of relying on traditional NLP metrics that measure surface-level text similarity, an LLM judge assesses qualities that matter to users, such as helpfulness, accuracy, and tone. The process involves giving the LLM a prompt that describes what \"good\" looks like along with the output to evaluate, and the model returns a score or judgment. This approach is effective because it frames evaluation as a focused classification task rather than open-ended generation.\n\nKnown biases of LLM-as-a-judge include:\n\n- **Position bias:** Judges tend to favor responses that appear first or last in their context window, causing the same response to receive different scores depending on position.\n- **Verbosity bias:** Judges often rate longer responses higher, even when concise answers would be more appropriate.\n- **Inconsistency:** The same judge with the same prompt can score the same response differently across runs, leading to noisy evaluation results.\n- **Self-enhancement bias:** Models may score their own outputs higher than those from other models.\n- **Provenance/recency bias:** Judges may favor stylistic patterns or phrasing associated with recent training data.\n\nThese biases can undermine evaluation reliability, so calibration against human judgment and mitigation strategies are important to improve trustworthiness."
}
Output:

